article.headline: Blazers' comeback from 14 down falls short
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- After the lead changed hands for the fourth time in 40 seconds, the undermanned Portland Trail Blazers called timeout and set up a play with second-year player Richie Frahm inbounding the ball -- a dangerous move against a Washington Wizards team that leads the league in steals. Gilbert Arenas, who had just given Washington the lead, intercepted the bounce pass and scored on a breakaway dunk with 21 seconds to play to help lift the Wizards to a 104-100 victory Wednesday night. "When you have a rookie taking the ball out of bounds, and it's coming down to the wire, he doesn't want to make that play," Arenas said. "I just shot the lane when he was making the pass." Arenas finished with 26 points, and Larry Hughes had 26 points, nine assists and six steals as Washington completed a perfect five-game homestand. The Wizards improved to 20-13, putting them seven games over .500 for the first time since they were 27-20 after a Jan. 30, 1985, victory over Chicago. "We have to build up the wins now for when things get thin later," Washington coach Eddie Jordan said. "We've got to be like squirrels. You've got to harvest your nuts right now." The Wizards also broke a seven-game home losing streak against Portland and improved to 7-5 against Western Conference teams. Once again, they made their work more difficult than necessary, blowing a 13-point fourth-quarter lead with a spate of missed free throws, but close games are becoming their trademark -- even if it drives Jordan crazy. "By now he should know that it's going to go down to the wire," Arenas said. "If he has a heart attack, that's his fault. If we haven't stopped anybody the whole game, we're going to do it in the last two minutes." Portland played most of the game without leading scorer Zach Randolph, who reinjured his right knee midway through the second quarter. The injury was described as a mild strain and will be reevaluated Thursday. The knee has been bothering Randolph recently, causing him to miss a game against Golden State on New Year's Day. Randolph's injury further depleted a Trail Blazers' frontcourt already missing Shareef Abdur-Rahim and Darius Miles. James Thomas, playing in his third NBA game on a 10-day contract, started the second half. Without Randolph, coach Maurice Cheeks opted to use Frahm in the crucial final possessions. "He obviously shouldn't have thrown that pass," Cheeks said. Damon Stoudamire had 23 points and 11 rebounds for the Trail Blazers, who are 1-2 midway through a six-game road trip. Nick Van Exel scored 19 points. "I guess the young guards outdueled the cagy veteran guards," Van Exel said. "It was a good battle, but they prevailed in the end. We made tough baskets, then they came right back and made tough baskets. I think they got the big defensive stop when Gilbert got the steal." Arenas and Hughes, the top scoring backcourt in the NBA, led the Wizards to an 84-71 lead with 8:36 to play, but Washington nearly blew the game by making just seven of 16 free throws in the fourth quarter. The Trail Blazers rallied to take the lead with 4:11 left after a 19-5 run. Van Exel made two 3-pointers in the final two minutes, setting up the seesaw finish. "It hurts. It hurts," Van Exel said. "It's nothing to be happy about, it's nothing to be excited about. Any loss that you get, it hurts."

Game notes
Etan Thomas made his season debut for the Wizards, scoring four points and grabbing four rebounds in 13 minutes. Thomas had been sidelined since October with an abdominal strain and was activated from the injured list before the game. Kwame Brown, whose ailing right ankle has caused him to miss five of the last six games, was placed on the injured list. ... Wizards guard Anthony Peeler missed the game with tendinitis in his right Achilles'. ... Joel Przybilla had a season-high 10 rebounds for Portland. ... Przybilla and Stoudamire started for the second straight game in place of benched starters Theo Ratliff and Derek Anderson.
